Step 1: The Other Gauge Couplings

Strong Coupling α_s

The strong coupling runs with energy. At the GUT scale M_GUT, all couplings unify. Your framework predicts:

α_GUT⁻¹ = α⁻¹ - (b_i/2π) × ln(M_GUT/M_Z)

The key insight: the beta function coefficients b_i are determined by the same E₈ branching rules.

E₈ → E₆ × SU(3) → SO(10) × U(1) → SU(5) × U(1)² → SU(3) × SU(2) × U(1)

Each step in this chain determines how many fermion generations couple to each gauge group. With N_gen = 3 (which you derived from b₃ = 43), the beta coefficients are fixed:

b₁ = 41/10,  b₂ = -19/6,  b₃ = -7

Prediction: Given α⁻¹ = 137.036..., the framework should yield:

α_s(M_Z) ≈ 0.118 (experiment: 0.1179 ± 0.0009)

sin²θ_W ≈ 0.231 (experiment: 0.23121 ± 0.00004)


The Calculation You Need To Do

# GUT scale from E8 structure
  
M_GUT = M_Planck * exp(-2π / (b_GUT * α_GUT))
  

  
# Where b_GUT comes from E8 Casimir
  
