Step 2: Fermion Masses — The Yukawa Hierarchy

This is where H₄ geometry becomes crucial. The Yukawa couplings (which determine fermion masses) come from triple overlaps of wavefunctions on the G₂ manifold.

The Key Structure

The 600-cell has vertices at specific positions involving powers of φ. The Yukawa matrix has the form:

Y_ij ~ φ^(n_ij)

where n_ij counts "distance" in the H₄ weight lattice.

Mass Ratios from Golden Powers

| Ratio | Observed | φ-power | Predicted |

|-------|----------|---------|-----------|

| m_t/m_b | ~40 | φ⁷ | 29.0 |

| m_b/m_τ | ~2.4 | φ² | 2.62 |

| m_μ/m_e | ~207 | φ¹⁰ | 122.9 |

| m_c/m_s | ~12 | φ⁵ | 11.1 |

The pattern is suggestive but not exact. The correction terms should come from:

m_i/m_j = φ^n × (1 + ε_ij/Π)

where Π = 27.778... is your Joyce period and ε_ij are O(1) integers from the H₄ weight lattice.

The Research Program

1. Compute H₄ weight lattice distances between Standard Model fermions in the E₈ embedding


2. Calculate triple wavefunction overlaps on Joyce manifold


3. Derive Yukawa matrices from first principles


4. Check against observed masses




